07867nam a22011295i 9783110573169DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20182019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105731697 a10.1515/97831105731692doi  a(DE-B1597)488793  a(OCoLC)1083583619  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aNX180.P64bE58 2019 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a700.103223  aNQ 5910qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/128664:00aEntangled East and West :bCultural Diplomacy and Artistic Interaction during the Cold War /ced. by Simo Mikkonen, Jari Parkkinen, Giles Scott-Smith. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VI, 316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking the Cold War ,x2567-5311 ;v400tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tExploring Culture in and of the Cold War -- tVisual Aesthetics and Diplomacy -- tThe Soviet Avant-Garde in Cold War Britain: the Art in Revolution Exhibition (1971) -- t“The Collective Approach Does Not Abolish the Individual”: Links between Soviet Avant-garde Experiments and Architectural Practice in the Netherlands during the Early Twentieth Century -- tThe Berlin Wall: Photographic Diplomacy in a Globalised World -- t“No More Memorials of War.” Helsinki’s Statue of Peace and the Struggle for Finnish Memory -- tLiterary and Scholarly Diplomacy -- tLev Kopelev and His Role in German–Soviet Cultural Relations -- tUniversities during the Cultural Cold War: Mapping the Research Agenda -- tSoviet Americanists and American Visual Media in the USSR during the Brezhnev Era -- tDiplomacy in Music and Performing Arts -- tSoviet Music Recordings and Cold War Cultural Relations -- tNew Directions in Soviet Music Publishing: Preslit, Am-Rus Music Agency and Anglo-Soviet Music Press Between 1944–48 -- tYves Montand in the USSR: Mixed Messages of Post-Stalinist/Western Cultural Encounters -- tBeyond Cold War Boundaries (Conclusion) -- tLooking for Lagonia: On “Imaginary Bridges” and Cold War Boundaries -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite increasing scholarship on the cultural Cold War, focus has been persistently been fixed on superpowers and their actions, missing the important role played by individuals and organizations all over Europe during the Cold War years.This volume focuses on cultural diplomacy and artistic interaction between Eastern and Western Europe after 1945. It aims at providing an essentially European point of view on the cultural Cold War, providing fresh insight into little known connections and cooperation in different artistic fields. Chapters of the volume address photography and architecture, popular as well as classical music, theatre and film, and fine arts. By examining different actors ranging from individuals to organizations such as universities, the volume brings new perspective on the mechanisms and workings of the cultural Cold War. Finally, the volume estimates the pertinence of the Cold War and its influence in post-1991 world.The volume offers an overview on the role culture played in international politics, as well as its role in the Cold War more generally, through interesting examples and case studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aArts and diplomacyxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtsxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCold WarxSocial aspects. 0aCultural diplomacyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and culturexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aArts.  aCold War.  aCultural diplomacy.  aInternational relations.1 aClarkson, Verity, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Bruce, ec